Definition 3.1. Let $(\mathcal{S},\,^{\ast_{0}},\,^{\ast},\iota)$ be a duplicated category of sets. It is called to satisfy the compactness axiom if the following condition holds. (Compactness axiom) Let $A:\Lambda\longrightarrow 2^{\,{}^{\ast}(X)}$ be a map such that $\Lambda,X$ are in $\mathcal{S}_{0}$ and every $A_{\lambda}$ is standard. If $\bigcap_{F}A\neq\phi$ for any finite subset $F\hookrightarrow{\Lambda}$, then $\bigcap_{\Lambda}A\neq\phi$. Or dually, (Compactness axiom) Let $A:\Lambda\longrightarrow 2^{\,{}^{\ast}(X)}$ be a map such that $\Lambda,X$ are in $\mathcal{S}_{0}$ and every $A_{\lambda}$ is standard. If $\bigcup_{\Lambda}A=\,^{\ast}(X)$, then $\bigcup_{F}A=\,^{\ast}(X)$ for some finite subset $F\hookrightarrow{\Lambda}$.
Definition 2.1. A quintet $(\mathcal{S}_{0},\mathcal{S},\,^{\ast_{0}},\,^{\ast},\iota)$ is called a duplicated category of sets if it satisfies the following: (i) $\mathcal{S}_{0}$ and $\mathcal{S}$ are categories which satisfy the axioms for $Sets$ ([3]). (ii) $\,{}^{\ast_{0}}:\mathcal{S}_{0}\longrightarrow\mathcal{S}$ is a functor which preserves all finite limits, subobject classifier $2$, exponentials and natural number objects. (iii) $\,{}^{\ast}:\mathcal{S}_{0}\longrightarrow\mathcal{S}$ is a functor which preserves all finite limits. (iv) $\iota:\,^{\ast_{0}}\longrightarrow\,^{\ast}$ is a natural transformation which satisfies $\iota_{X}=id_{\,{}^{\ast_{0}}(X)}=id_{\,{}^{\ast}(X)}$ for any finite object $X$ in $\mathcal{S}_{0}$. (Here $id$ denotes the identity map.)
Definition 2.7. We define a family of morphism $\kappa_{A,B}:\,^{\ast}(B^{A})\longrightarrow\,^{\ast}(B)^{\,{}^{\ast}(A)}$ by the lambda conversion of $\,{}^{\ast}(ev_{A,B}):\,^{\ast}(A\times B^{A})\cong\,^{\ast}(A)\times\,^{\ast}% (B^{A})\longrightarrow\,^{\ast}(B)$ for all pairs of objects in $A,B$ in $\mathcal{S}_{0}$. (Here $ev_{A,B}$ denotes the evaluation map.)
Definition 2.11. Let $A,B$ be objects in $\mathcal{S}_{0}$. A map $F:\,^{\ast}(A)\longrightarrow\,^{\ast}(B)$ is called standard or internal if its lambda conversion $\widehat{F}$ factors thorough $\kappa_{A,B}\circ\iota_{B^{A}}$ or $\kappa_{A,B}$, respectively. Otherwise, it is called external. If $f$ is internal but not standard, it is is called nonstandard.
Definition 4.4. Let $x$ be a morphism in $\mathcal{O}(m,n)$ with terminus less than $t$. Then the $t$-cone on $x$ is the morphism $\rho_{t}x$ in $\mathcal{O}(m+1,n)$ given on basis elements as follows: $(\rho_{t}x)[m+1]=[t]$; if $x[\mathbf{a}]=\sum_{\mathbf{b}}x_{\mathbf{a}\mathbf{b}}[\mathbf{b}]$ then $(\rho_{t}x)[\mathbf{a}]=\sum_{\mathbf{b}}x_{\mathbf{a}\mathbf{b}}[\mathbf{b}],% \quad(\rho_{t}x)[\mathbf{a},m+1]=\sum_{\mathbf{b}}x_{\mathbf{a}\mathbf{b}}[% \mathbf{b},t].$
Definition 3.5. Let $m$ and $i$ be integers with $0\leq i\leq m-1$. If $x$ and $y$ are chain maps in $\mathbf{Z}\Delta(m,n)$ such that $\partial_{i}x=\partial_{i+1}y$, then the wedge $x\wedge_{i}y$ is the chain map in $\mathbf{Z}\Delta(m+1,n)$ given by $x\wedge_{i}y=\epsilon_{i+1}x-\epsilon_{i}^{2}\partial_{i+1}y+\epsilon_{i}y.$
Definition 3.2. Let $x$ be a chain map in $\mathbf{Z}\Delta(m,n)$. For $m>0$ and $0\leq i\leq m$, the face $\partial_{i}x$ is the chain map in $\mathbf{Z}\Delta(m-1,n)$ given on basis elements by $(\partial_{i}x)[\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}]=x[\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}^{\prime}],$ where the terms of $\mathbf{b}$ are less than $i$, the terms of $\mathbf{c}$ are greater than or equal to $i$, and the terms of $\mathbf{c}^{\prime}$ are obtained from those of $\mathbf{c}$ by adding $1$. For $0\leq i\leq m$ the degeneracy $\epsilon_{i}x$ is the chain map in $\mathbf{Z}\Delta(m+1,n)$ given on basis elements by $\displaystyle(\epsilon_{i}x)[\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}]=x[\mathbf{b},\mathbf{c}^{% \prime\prime}],$ $\displaystyle(\epsilon_{i}x)[\mathbf{b},i,\mathbf{c}]=(\epsilon_{i}x)[\mathbf{% b},i+1,\mathbf{c}]=x[\mathbf{b},i,\mathbf{c}^{\prime\prime}],$ $\displaystyle(\epsilon_{i}x)[\mathbf{b},i,i+1,\mathbf{c}]=0,$ where the terms of $\mathbf{b}$ are less than $i$, the terms of $\mathbf{c}$ are greater than $i+1$, and the terms of $\mathbf{c}^{\prime\prime}$ are obtained from those of $\mathbf{c}$ by subtracting $1$.
Definition 8.1. Let $S$ be a subset of a set with complicial identities, let $U$ be a set with complicial identities, and let $k$ be a nonnegative integer. Then a partial morphism of degree $k$ from $S$ to $U$ is a function $f\colon S\to U$ which increases degrees by $k$ and which satisfies the following conditions. (1) If $x$ is an $m$-dimensional member of $S$ with $m>0$ and if $0\leq i\leq m$, then $\partial_{i}x\in S$ and $f\partial_{i}x=\partial_{i}fx$. (2) If $x$ is a $1$-dimensional member of $S$ and $x\in\operatorname{im}\epsilon_{0}$ then $fx\in\operatorname{im}\epsilon_{0}$. (3) If $x\in S$ and $x\in\operatorname{im}\wedge_{i}$ then $fx\in\operatorname{im}\wedge_{i}$.
Definition 4.2. Let $x$ be a morphism in $\mathcal{O}(m,n)$. Then the terminus of $x$, denoted $\operatorname{terminus}x$, is the integer $t$ such that $x[m]=[t]$; the rank of $x$, denoted $\operatorname{rank}x$, is the number of zero-dimensional basis elements $[a]$ in $\mathbf{Z}\Delta(m)$ such that $x[a]\neq x[m]$; the corank of $x$, denoted $\operatorname{corank}x$, is the number of zero-dimensional basis elements $[a]$ in $\mathbf{Z}\Delta(m)$ such that $a<m$ and $x[a]=x[m]$.
Definition 3.1. A simplicial set $X$ is a sequence of sets $X_{0},X_{1},\ldots\,$ together with face operations $\partial_{i}\colon X_{m}\to X_{m-1}\quad(m>0,\ 0\leq i\leq m)$ and degeneracy operations $\epsilon_{i}\colon X_{m}\to X_{m+1}\quad(0\leq i\leq m)$ such that $\displaystyle\partial_{i}\partial_{j}=\partial_{j-1}\partial_{i}\quad(i<j),$ $\displaystyle\partial_{i}\epsilon_{j}=\epsilon_{j-1}\partial_{i}\quad(i<j),$ $\displaystyle\partial_{i}\epsilon_{i}=\partial_{i+1}\epsilon_{i}=\operatorname% {id},$ $\displaystyle\partial_{i}\epsilon_{j}=\epsilon_{j}\partial_{i-1}\quad(i>j+1),$ $\displaystyle\epsilon_{i}\epsilon_{j}=\epsilon_{j+1}\epsilon_{i}\quad(i\leq j).$
Definition 6.1. A set with complicial identities is a simplicial set $X$, together with wedges $x\wedge_{i}y\in X_{m+1},$ defined when $x,y\in X_{m}$ and $\partial_{i}x=\partial_{i+1}y$, such that the following axioms hold. (1) If $x\wedge_{i}y$ is defined with $x,y\in X_{m}$, then $\displaystyle\partial_{j}(x\wedge_{i}y)=\partial_{j}x\wedge_{i-1}\partial_{j}y% \quad(0\leq j<i),$ $\displaystyle\partial_{i}(x\wedge_{i}y)=y,$ $\displaystyle\partial_{i+2}(x\wedge_{i}y)=x,$ $\displaystyle\partial_{j}(x\wedge_{i}y)=\partial_{j-1}x\wedge_{i}\partial_{j-1% }y\quad(i+3\leq j\leq m+1).$ (2) If $x\in X_{m}$ and $0\leq i<m$ then $\epsilon_{i}x=\epsilon_{i}\partial_{i+1}x\wedge_{i}x,\quad\epsilon_{i+1}x=x% \wedge_{i}\epsilon_{i}\partial_{i}x.$ (3) If $A$ is of the form $b\wedge_{i}(y\wedge_{i}z)$ then $A=(\partial_{i+2}b\wedge_{i}y)\wedge_{i+1}\partial_{i+1}A.$ (4) If $A$ is of the form $(x\wedge_{i}y)\wedge_{i+1}c$ then $A=\partial_{i+2}A\wedge_{i}(y\wedge_{i}\partial_{i}c).$ (5) The equality $[x\wedge_{i}\partial_{i+1}(y\wedge_{i}z)]\wedge_{i}(y\wedge_{i}z)=(x\wedge_{i}% y)\wedge_{i+1}[\partial_{i+1}(x\wedge_{i}y)\wedge_{i}z]$ holds whenever either side is defined. (6) If $A$ is of the form $\partial_{i+2}[(x\wedge_{i+1}y)\wedge_{i+1}(y\wedge_{i}z)]$, then the equality $A\wedge_{i}(w\wedge_{i+1}\partial_{i}A)=(\partial_{i+3}A\wedge_{i}w)\wedge_{i+% 2}A$ holds whenever either side is defined. (7) If $i\leq j-3$ then the equality $(x\wedge_{i}y)\wedge_{j}(z\wedge_{i}w)=(x\wedge_{j-1}z)\wedge_{i}(y\wedge_{j-1% }w)$ holds whenever either side is defined. A morphism of sets with complicial identities $f\colon X\to Y$ is a sequence of functions $f\colon X_{m}\to Y_{m}$ commuting with the face, degeneracy and wedge operations.
Definition 3.9 Let $G$ be a cubical $\omega$-category. The $\omega$-category $\gamma G$ associated to $G$ is the colimit of the sequence $\xymatrix@1{\Phi_{0}(G_{0})\ar[r]^{\varepsilon_{1}}&\Phi_{1}(G_{1})\ar[r]^{% \varepsilon_{1}}&\Phi_{2}(G_{2})\ar[r]&\cdots.}$
Definition 9.1 Let $x$ be a member of $G_{n}$. Then $x$ is thin if $\mathrm{dim}\;x(I^{n})<n.$
Definition 1.2 An $\omega$-category of sets is an $\omega$-category $X$ whose members are sets such that $x\mathbin{\#}_{p}y=x\cup y$ whenever $x\mathbin{\#}_{p}y$ is defined in $X$.
Definition 6.9 Let $\sigma$ be a cell in $I^{n}$, and let the dimension of $\sigma$ be $m$. Then $\partial_{\sigma}:G_{m}\to G_{n}$ is the cubical $\omega$-category operation of the form $\partial^{\alpha(1)}_{i(1)}\ldots\partial^{\alpha(n-m)}_{i(n-m)}$ such that the underlying homomorphism $\check{\partial}_{\sigma}\colon M(I^{m})\to M(I^{n})$ sends $I^{m}$ to $\sigma$.
Definition 2.3 The cubical nerve of an $\omega$-category $X$ is the cubical $\omega$-category $\lambda X$ defined as follows: $(\lambda X)_{n}=\mathop{\rm Hom}\nolimits[M(I^{n}),X],$ and the operations $\partial^{\alpha}_{i}$, $\varepsilon_{i}$, $\circ_{i}$, $\Gamma^{\alpha}_{i}$ are induced by $\check{\partial}^{\alpha}_{i}$, $\check{\varepsilon}_{i}$, $\check{\mu}_{i}$, $\check{\Gamma}^{\alpha}_{i}$ according to the formulae $\partial^{\alpha}_{i}x=x\circ\check{\partial}^{\alpha}_{i}\colon M(I^{n-1})\to X$ for $x\colon M(I^{n})\to X$, etc.
Definition 10.3 Let $F,G$ be cubical $\omega$-categories. Then $F\otimes G$ is the cubical $\omega$-category generated by elements in dimension $n\geqslant 0$ of the form $x\otimes y$ where $x\in F_{p},\;y\in G_{q}$ and $p+q=n$, subject to the following defining relations (plus, of course, the laws for cubical $\omega$-categories): (i) $\partial^{\alpha}_{i}(x\otimes y)=\begin{cases}(\partial^{\alpha}_{i}x)\otimes y% &\text{if }1\leqslant i\leqslant p,\\ x\otimes(\partial^{\alpha}_{i-p}y)&\text{if }p+1\leqslant i\leqslant n;\end{cases}$ (ii) $\varepsilon_{i}(x\otimes y)=\begin{cases}(\varepsilon_{i}x)\otimes y&\text{if % }1\leqslant i\leqslant p+1,\\ x\otimes(\varepsilon_{i-p}y)&\text{if }p+1\leqslant i\leqslant n+1;\end{cases}$ (iii) $\Gamma^{\alpha}_{i}(x\otimes y)=\begin{cases}(\Gamma^{\alpha}_{i}x)\otimes y&% \text{if }1\leqslant i\leqslant p,\\ x\otimes(\Gamma^{\alpha}_{i-p}y)&\text{if }p+1\leqslant i\leqslant n;\end{cases}$ (iv) $(x\circ_{i}x^{\prime})\otimes y=(x\otimes y)\circ_{i}(x^{\prime}\otimes y)$ if $1\leqslant i\leqslant p,$ and $x\circ_{i}x^{\prime}$ is defined in $F;$ (v) $x\otimes(y\circ_{j}y^{\prime})=(x\otimes y)\circ_{p+j}(x\otimes y^{\prime})$ if $1\leqslant j\leqslant q,$ and $y\circ_{j}y^{\prime}$ is defined in $G;$
Definition 6.2 A generalised $\psi_{i}$ is an operator of the form $\psi_{i}$ or $\varepsilon_{i}\partial^{\alpha}_{i}$ or $\varepsilon_{i}\partial^{\alpha}_{i+1}$. A generalised $\Psi_{r}$ is an operator of the form $\psi^{\prime}_{r-1}\psi^{\prime}_{r-2}\ldots\psi^{\prime}_{1}$, where $\psi^{\prime}_{i}$ is a generalised $\psi_{i}$. A generalised $\Phi_{m}$ is an operator of the form $\Psi^{\prime}_{1}\Psi^{\prime}_{2}\ldots\Psi^{\prime}_{m}$, where $\Psi^{\prime}_{r}$ is a generalised $\Psi_{r}$.
Definition 2.1 A cubical $\omega$-category with connections $G=\{G_{n}\}$ is a cubical set with connections and compositions such that each $\circ_{j}$ is a category structure on $G_{n}$ with identity elements $\varepsilon_{j}y\;(y\in G_{n-1})$, and in addition $\Gamma^{+}_{i}x\circ_{i}\Gamma^{-}_{i}x=\varepsilon_{i+1}x,\quad\Gamma^{+}_{i}% x\circ_{i+1}\Gamma^{-}_{i}x=\varepsilon_{i}x.$ For simplicity, a cubical $\omega$-category with connections will be called a cubical $\omega$-category in the rest of this paper.
Definition 9.4 For $n>0$ an $n$-shell $z$ in $G$ is commutative if $z(d^{-}_{n-1}I^{n})=z(d^{+}_{n-1}I^{n}).$
Definition 1.1 An $\omega$-category is a set $X$ together with unary operations $d^{-}_{p}$, $d^{+}_{p}$ and partially defined binary operations $\mathbin{\#}_{p}$ for $p=0$, $1$, … such that the following conditions hold: (i) $x\mathbin{\#}_{p}y$ is defined if and only if $d^{+}_{p}x=d^{-}_{p}y$; (ii) $d^{\beta}_{q}d^{\alpha}_{p}x=\begin{cases}d^{\beta}_{q}x&\text{for }q<p,\\ d^{\alpha}_{p}x&\text{for }q\geqslant p;\end{cases}$ (iii) if $x\mathbin{\#}_{p}y$ is defined then $\displaystyle d^{-}_{p}(x\mathbin{\#}_{p}y)$ $\displaystyle=d^{-}_{p}x,$ $\displaystyle d^{+}_{p}(x\mathbin{\#}_{p}y)$ $\displaystyle=d^{+}_{p}y,$ $\displaystyle d^{\beta}_{q}(x\mathbin{\#}_{p}y)$ $\displaystyle=d^{\beta}_{q}x\mathbin{\#}_{p}d^{\beta}_{q}y\ \text{for }q\neq p;$ (iv) $d^{-}_{p}x\mathbin{\#}_{p}x=x\mathbin{\#}_{p}d^{+}_{p}x=x$; (v) $(x\mathbin{\#}_{p}y)\mathbin{\#}_{p}z=x\mathbin{\#}_{p}(y\mathbin{\#}_{p}z)$ if either side is defined; (vi) if $p\neq q$ then $(x\mathbin{\#}_{p}y)\mathbin{\#}_{q}(x^{\prime}\mathbin{\#}_{p}y^{\prime})=(x% \mathbin{\#}_{q}x^{\prime})\mathbin{\#}_{p}(y\mathbin{\#}_{q}y^{\prime})$ whenever both sides are defined; (vii) for each $x\in X$ there is a dimension $\dim x$ such that $d^{\alpha}_{p}x=x$ if and only if $p\geqslant\dim x$.
Definition 8.2 Let $G$ be a cubical $\omega$-category and let $n$ be a positive integer. An $n$-shell in $G$ an ordered $(2n)$-tuple $z=(z^{-}_{1},z^{+}_{1},\ldots,z^{-}_{n},z^{+}_{n})$ of members of $G_{n-1}$ such that $\partial^{\alpha}_{i}z^{\beta}_{j}=\partial^{\beta}_{j-1}z^{\alpha}_{i}$ whenever $i<j$. The set of $n$-shells is denoted $\Box G_{n-1}$.
Definition 3.1 Let $G$ be a cubical $\omega$-category. The folding operations are the operations $\psi_{i},\Psi_{r},\Phi_{m}\colon G_{n}\to G_{n}$ defined for $1\leqslant i\leqslant n-1$, $1\leqslant r\leqslant n$ and $0\leqslant m\leqslant n$ by $\displaystyle\psi_{i}x=\Gamma^{+}_{i}\partial^{-}_{i+1}x\circ_{i+1}x\circ_{i+1% }\Gamma^{-}_{i}\partial^{+}_{i+1}x,$ $\displaystyle\Psi_{r}=\psi_{r-1}\psi_{r-2}\ldots\psi_{1},$ $\displaystyle\Phi_{m}=\Psi_{1}\Psi_{2}\ldots\Psi_{m}=\psi_{1}(\psi_{2}\psi_{1}% )\ldots(\psi_{m-1}\ldots\psi_{1}).$
Definitions 2.4. Let $\Lambda$ be a rank $k$ graph. For $\lambda\in\Lambda$ define $Z(\lambda)=\{\lambda x\in\Lambda^{\infty}:s(\lambda)=x(0)\}=\{x:x(0,d(\lambda)% )=\lambda\}.$
Definition 4.3. The $k$-graph $\Lambda$ is said to satisfy the aperiodicity condition (A) if for every $v\in\Lambda^{0}$ there is an aperiodic path $x\in\Lambda^{\infty}(v)$.
Definitions 1.4. The $k$-graph $\Lambda$ is row finite if for each $m\in{\bf N}^{k}$ and $v\in\Lambda^{0}$ the set $\Lambda^{m}(v):=\{\lambda\in\Lambda^{m}:r(\lambda)=v\}$ is finite. Similarly $\Lambda$ has no sources if $\Lambda^{m}(v)\neq\emptyset$ for all $v\in\Lambda^{0}$ and $m\in{\bf N}^{k}$.
Definition 1.9. Let $f:{\bf N}^{\ell}\rightarrow{\bf N}^{k}$ be a monoid morphism, then if $(\Lambda,d)$ is a $k$-graph we may form the $\ell$-graph $f^{*}(\Lambda)$ as follows: (the objects of $f^{*}(\Lambda)$ may be identified with those of $\Lambda$ and) $f^{*}(\Lambda)=\{(\lambda,n):d(\lambda)=f(n)\}$ with $d(\lambda,n)=n$, $s(\lambda,n)=s(\lambda)$ and $r(\lambda,n)=r(\lambda)$.
Definition 2.7. If $\Lambda$ is $k$-graph then let ${\mathcal{G}}_{\Lambda}=\{(x,n,y)\in\Lambda^{\infty}\times{\bf Z}^{k}\times% \Lambda^{\infty}:\sigma^{\ell}x=\sigma^{m}y,n=\ell-m\}.$ Define range and source maps $r,s:{\mathcal{G}}_{\Lambda}\rightarrow\Lambda^{\infty}$ by $r(x,n,y)=x$, $s(x,n,y)=y$. For $(x,n,y)$, $(y,\ell,z)\in{\mathcal{G}}_{\Lambda}$ set $(x,n,y)(y,\ell,z)=(x,n+\ell,z)$, and $(x,n,y)^{-1}=(y,-n,x)$; ${\mathcal{G}}_{\Lambda}$ is called the path groupoid of $\Lambda$ (cf. [R, D, KPRR]).
Definitions 1.5. Let $\Lambda$ be a row finite $k$-graph with no sources. Then $C^{*}(\Lambda)$ is defined to be the universal $C^{*}$–algebra generated by a family $\{s_{\lambda}:\lambda\in\Lambda\}$ of partial isometries satisfying: (i) $\{s_{v}:v\in\Lambda^{0}\}$ is a family of mutually orthogonal projections, (ii) $s_{\lambda\mu}=s_{\lambda}s_{\mu}$ for all $\lambda,\mu\in\Lambda$ such that $s(\lambda)=r(\mu)$, (iii) $s_{\lambda}^{*}s_{\lambda}=s_{s(\lambda)}$ for all $\lambda\in\Lambda$, (iv) for all $v\in\Lambda^{0}$ and $n\in{\bf N}^{k}$ we have $\displaystyle s_{v}=\sum_{\lambda\in\Lambda^{n}(v)}s_{\lambda}s_{\lambda}^{*}$. For $\lambda\in\Lambda$, define $p_{\lambda}=s_{\lambda}s_{\lambda}^{*}$ (note that $p_{v}=s_{v}$ for all $v\in\Lambda^{0}$). A family of partial isometries satisfying (i)–(iv) above is called a $*$–representation of $\Lambda$.
Definitions 1.1. A $k$-graph (rank $k$ graph or higher rank graph) $(\Lambda,d)$ consists of a countable small category $\Lambda$ (with range and source maps $r$ and $s$ respectively) together with a functor $d:\Lambda\rightarrow{\bf N}^{k}$ satisfying the factorisation property: for every $\lambda\in\Lambda$ and $m,n\in{\bf N}^{k}$ with $d(\lambda)=m+n$, there are unique elements $\mu,\nu\in\Lambda$ such that $\lambda=\mu\nu$ and $d(\mu)=m$, $d(\nu)=n$. For $n\in{\bf N}^{k}$ we write $\Lambda^{n}:=d^{-1}(n)$. A morphism between $k$-graphs $(\Lambda_{1},d_{1})$ and $(\Lambda_{2},d_{2})$ is a functor $f:\Lambda_{1}\rightarrow\Lambda_{2}$ compatible with the degree maps.
Definition 4.7. We say that $\Lambda$ is cofinal if for every $x\in\Lambda^{\infty}$ and $v\in\Lambda^{0}$ there is $\lambda\in\Lambda$ and $n\in{\bf N}^{k}$ such that $s(\lambda)=x(n)$ and $r(\lambda)=v$.
Definitions 2.1. Let $\Lambda$ be a $k$-graph, then $\Lambda^{\infty}~{}=~{}\{x:\Omega_{k}\rightarrow\Lambda:x\;\mbox{is a $k$-% graph morphism}\},$ is the infinite path space of $\Lambda$. For $v\in\Lambda^{0}$ let $\Lambda^{\infty}(v)=\{x\in\Lambda^{\infty}:x(0)=v\}$. For each $p\in{\bf N}^{k}$ define $\sigma^{p}:\Lambda^{\infty}\rightarrow\Lambda^{\infty}$ by $\sigma^{p}(x)(m,n)=x(m+p,n+p)$ for $x\in\Lambda^{\infty}$ and $(m,n)\in\Omega$. (Note that $\sigma^{p+q}=\sigma^{p}\circ\sigma^{q}$).
Definition 5.1. Let $G$ be a discrete group, $(\Lambda,d)$ a $k$-graph. Given $c:\Lambda\rightarrow G$ a functor then define the skew product $G\times_{c}\Lambda$ as follows: the objects are identified with $G\times\Lambda^{0}$ and the morphisms are identified with $G\times\Lambda$ with the following structure maps $s(g,\lambda)=(gc(\lambda),s(\lambda))\quad\mbox{and}\quad r(g,\lambda)=(g,r(% \lambda)).$ If $s(\lambda)=r(\mu)$ then $(g,\lambda)$ and $(gc(\lambda),\mu)$ are composable in $G\times_{c}\Lambda$ and $(g,\lambda)(gc(\lambda),\mu)=(g,\lambda\mu).$ The degree map is given by $d(g,\lambda)=d(\lambda)$.
Definitions 4.1. For $x\in\Lambda^{\infty}$ and $p\in{\bf Z}^{k}$ we say that $p$ is a period of $x$ if for every $(m,n)\in\Omega$ with $m+p\geq 0$ we have $x(m+p,n+p)=x(m,n)$. We say that $x$ is periodic if it has a nonzero period. We say that $x$ is eventually periodic if $\sigma^{n}x$ is periodic for some $n\in{\bf N}^{k}$, otherwise $x$ is said to be aperiodic.
Definition 1 A (single sorted algebraic) 2-theory is a 2-category ${\bf T}$ with a given coproduct structure and a 2-functor $G_{{\bf T}}:\overline{\bf Fin}_{sk}\longrightarrow{\bf T}$ such that $G_{{\bf T}}$ is bijective on 0-cells and preserves the coproduct structure.
Definition 5.9. Let $L_{1},L_{2}\colon{\mathcal{M}}\rightarrow{\mathcal{N}}$ be two maps between model categories. (a) A Quillen homotopy between the maps $L_{1}$ and $L_{2}$ is a natural transformation $L_{1}\rightarrow L_{2}$ with the property that $L_{1}X\rightarrow L_{2}X$ is a weak equivalence whenever $X$ is cofibrant. (b) As expected, two maps are Quillen-homotopic if they can be connected by a zig-zag of Quillen homotopies.
Definition 7.2. Suppose ${\mathcal{C}}$ is a Grothendieck site with topology ${\mathcal{T}}$. Then $U{\mathcal{C}}/{{\mathcal{T}}}$ denotes the model category obtained by forming the universal model category $U{\mathcal{C}}$ and then localizing at the set of maps $\{\operatorname*{hocolim}U_{*}\rightarrow X\}$, where $X$ runs through all objects of ${\mathcal{C}}$ and $U_{*}$ runs through all hypercovers of $X$.
Definition 3.3. Let $\Gamma_{1}$ and $\Gamma_{2}$ be two cosimplicial resolutions of a map $\gamma:{\mathcal{C}}\rightarrow{\mathcal{M}}$. A map of resolutions $\Gamma_{1}\rightarrow\Gamma_{2}$ is a natural transformation $\Gamma_{1}(X)\rightarrow\Gamma_{2}(X)$ making the following triangle commute: $\xymatrix{\Gamma_{1}(X)\ar[rr]\ar[dr]&&\Gamma_{2}(X)\ar[dl]\\ &c^{*}X}$ The category of cosimplicial resolutions on $\gamma$ will be denoted $\operatorname{coRes}(\gamma)$. A map of simplicial resolutions, as well as the category $\operatorname{sRes}(\gamma)$, are defined similarly.
Definition 6.2. A model category ${\mathcal{M}}$ is called combinatorial if it is cofibrantly-generated and the underlying category is locally presentable. The latter means that there is a regular cardinal $\lambda$ and a set of objects ${\mathcal{A}}$ in ${\mathcal{M}}$ such that (i) Every object in ${\mathcal{A}}$ is small with respect to $\lambda$-filtered colimits, and (ii) Every object of ${\mathcal{M}}$ can be expressed as a $\lambda$-filtered colimit of elements of ${\mathcal{A}}$.
Definition 5.3. (a) An S-local object of ${\mathcal{M}}$ is a fibrant object $X$ such that for every map $A\rightarrow B$ in $S$, the induced map of homotopy function complexes $\underline{{\mathcal{M}}}(B,X)\rightarrow\underline{{\mathcal{M}}}(A,X)$ is a weak equivalence of simplicial sets. (b) An S-local equivalence is a map $A\rightarrow B$ such that $\underline{{\mathcal{M}}}(B,X)\rightarrow\underline{{\mathcal{M}}}(A,X)$ is a weak equivalence for every $S$-local object $X$.
Definition 3.1. Let ${\mathcal{M}}$ be a model category and let $X$ be an object. (a) A cosimplicial resolution of $X$ is a Reedy cofibrant object $\Gamma\in c{\mathcal{M}}$ together with a map $\Gamma\rightarrow c^{*}X$ which is a weak equivalence in every dimension. Here $c^{*}X$ is the constant cosimplicial object with $X$ in every level. (b) A simplicial resolution of $X$ is a Reedy fibrant object $\Phi$ in $s{\mathcal{M}}$ together with a map $c_{*}X\rightarrow\Phi$ which is a weak equivalence in every dimension.
Definition 6.1. Let ${\mathcal{M}}$ be a model category. A small presentation of ${\mathcal{M}}$ consists of the following data: (1) a small category ${\mathcal{C}}$, (2) a choice of Quillen pair $Re:U{\mathcal{C}}\rightleftarrows{\mathcal{M}}:Sing$, (3) a set of maps $S$ in $U{\mathcal{C}}$, and we require the properties that (a) The left derived functor of $Re$ takes maps in $S$ to weak equivalences; (b) The induced Quillen pair $U{\mathcal{C}}/S\rightleftarrows{\mathcal{M}}$ is a Quillen equivalence.
Definition 5.2. Let ${\mathcal{M}}$ be a model category and let $S$ be a set of maps in ${\mathcal{M}}$. An $S$-localization of ${\mathcal{M}}$ is a model category ${\mathcal{M}}/S$ and a map $F\colon{\mathcal{M}}\rightarrow{\mathcal{M}}/S$ such that the following holds: (a) $F^{cof}$ takes maps in $S$ to weak-equivalences, and (b) $F$ is initial among maps satisfying (a). (Recall that $F^{cof}$—which we call the left derived functor of $F$—denotes any functor obtained by pre-composing $F$ with a cofibrant-replacement functor.)
Definition 9.2. A simplicial presheaf $F$ has free degeneracies if there exist sub-presheaves $N_{k}\hookrightarrow F_{k}$ such that the canonical map $\coprod_{\sigma}N_{\sigma}\rightarrow F_{k}$ is an isomorphism: here the variable $\sigma$ ranges over all surjective maps in $\Delta$ of the form $[k]\rightarrow[n]$, $N_{\sigma}$ denotes a copy of $N_{n}$, and the map $N_{\sigma}\rightarrow F_{k}$ is the one induced by $\sigma^{*}\colon F_{n}\rightarrow F_{k}$. (This is called a splitting of $F$ in [AM, Def. 8.1]).
Definition 5.4. A Bousfield S-localization of ${\mathcal{M}}$ is a model category ${\mathcal{M}}/S$ with the properties that (a) The underlying category of ${\mathcal{M}}/S$ is ${\mathcal{M}}$; (b) The cofibrations in ${\mathcal{M}}/S$ are the same as those in ${\mathcal{M}}$; (c) The weak equivalences in ${\mathcal{M}}/S$ are the $S$-local equivalences.
Definition 3.2. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a category with a functor $\gamma\colon{\mathcal{C}}\rightarrow{\mathcal{M}}$. A cosimplicial resolution of $\gamma$ is (i) a functor $\Gamma:{\mathcal{C}}\rightarrow c{\mathcal{M}}$ such that each $\Gamma(X)$ is Reedy cofibrant, and (ii) a natural weak equivalence $\Gamma(X)\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{\longrightarrow}}c^{*}X$, Simplicial resolutions of $\gamma$ are defined similarly.
Definition 7.1. Let $X\in{\mathcal{C}}$ and suppose that $U_{*}$ is a simplicial presheaf with a map $U_{*}\rightarrow rX$. This map is called a hypercover of $X$ if (i) Each $U_{n}$ is a coproduct of representables, (ii) $U_{0}\rightarrow rX$ is a cover, and (iii) For every integer $n\geq 1$, the component of $U^{\Delta^{n}}\rightarrow U^{\partial\Delta^{n}}$ in degree $0$ is a cover.
Definition 1.3. In a regular doctrine $(\mathbb{C},P)$, a morphism $f:A\longrightarrow B$ of $\mathbb{C}$ is said to be internally bijective whenever $\delta_{A}=(f\times f)^{*}\delta_{B}$ $\top_{B}=\exists_{f}\top_{A}$ i.e. whenever $f$ is internally injective and surjective.
Definition 1.2. A doctrine is regular if for each arrow $f:X\longrightarrow Y$ in $\mathbb{C}$ there exists a functor $\exists_{f}\dashv f^{*}$ satisfying - Beck-Chevalley condition: i.e. for every pullback of the form $\xymatrix{X\ar[d]_{-}{g}\ar[r]^{-}{f}&Y\ar[d]^{h}\\ Z\ar[r]_{-}{k}&W}$ it holds that $\exists_{f}\circ g^{*}=h^{*}\circ\exists_{k}$ - Frobenius Reciprocity: i.e. $\exists_{f}(\alpha\wedge f^{*}\beta)=\exists_{f}\alpha\wedge\beta$.
Definition 1.6. A regular doctrine $(\mathbb{C},P)$ is said to admit sheafification if $P$-Shv is reflective.
